    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "t_start": 0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "An ultracold cesium gas. A researcher sweeps a magnetic field. At one precise field value, the scattering cross-section spikes by a factor of ten thousand.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.93,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "t_start": 9,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "A few milligauss away, the cross-section collapses back. Right at that field, a new two-body bound state has flickered into existence at zero binding energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.64,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "t_start": 18,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Well depth changing smoothly should change cross-sections smoothly. Yet adding one barely-bound state sends the cross-section to infinity. Why?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "Well depth changing smoothly should change cross-sections smoothly. Yet adding one\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "THE QUESTION",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B03.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "headline": "One new bound state. Cross-section: infinity.",
        "dek": "Why does a barely-bound state at threshold send the cross-section to infinity?"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.27,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 27,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "At low energy, the scattering cross-section depends on one number: the scattering length. A bigger scattering length means a bigger effective target area.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.01,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 36,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "The cross-section is four pi times the scattering length squared. Normally the scattering length is just a few nanometers \u2014 a reasonable number.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.07,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 45,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "But when a bound state exists at exactly zero energy \u2014 exactly at threshold \u2014 the wave function barely decays outside the well. The decay length becomes enormous.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
        "source": "ai",
        "motion": "kenburns",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "But when a bound state exists at exactly zero energy \u2014\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "THE PROBLEM",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B06.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.29,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 55,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Here is a potential well, and its bound state. As the binding energy shrinks toward zero, the wave function leaks further and further outside the well.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.96,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 65,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "At exactly zero binding energy, the wave function never fully decays. It extends to infinity outside. The decay length, which is also the scattering length, diverges.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.45,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 75,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Plot the scattering length against well depth. Each time a new bound state appears at threshold, the scattering length passes through plus and minus infinity \u2014 a sign flip and a divergence.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.83,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-feshbach-resonance/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 86,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Since the cross-section goes as scattering length squared, it diverges as infinity squared \u2014 infinity. The particle sees an infinitely large target because the bound state has no preferred size.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
